ical purposes, commercialized first, and so there are a lot of Bitcoin =0Am=
iners out there. But AI is plausibly bigger and more lucrative now, so ther=
e =0Aare some Bitcoin miners who are surprised and relieved to find that, a=
ctually, =0Athey can get into the AI business. Othersneed a push though =0A=
<https://www.wsj.com/finance/currencies/activist-starboard-value-takes-stak=
e-in-bitcoin-mining-company-riot-82b3796f>=0A:=0A=0AActivist investor Starb=
oard Value has built a significant position in Riot =0APlatforms and is pus=
hing for changes at the bitcoin-mining operator, according =0Ato people fam=
iliar with the matter. ...=0A=0AAs a crypto miner, Riot uses high-powered c=
omputers to process bitcoin =0Atransactions by solving complex mathematical=
 problems, receiving bitcoin as =0Apayment.=0A=0AStarboard has been in disc=
ussions with Riot=E2=80=99s management team to push the =0Acompany to conve=
rt some of its bitcoin-mining facilities into capacity for =0Aso-called hyp=
erscalers, or large data-center users, the people said.=0A=0AHyperscalers a=
re companies that operate large-scale data centers designed to =0Ahandle ma=
ssive amounts of computing power and storage capacity. Data centers =0Aoper=
ated by companies such as Amazon Web Services and Alphabet=E2=80=99s Google=
 Cloud =0Ahave grown increasingly important as the artificial-intelligence =
boom gobbles =0Aup even more computing power and resources.=0A=0AIt really =
is an amazing coincidence that not only were crypto and AI roughly =0Aconse=
cutive booms led by, often, the same sorts of entrepreneurs and backed by =
=0Athe same sorts of venture capitalists, but also that they run on similar=
 =0Ainfrastructure. You could imagine the crypto boom collapsing and leavin=
